Here's a complete example. I'll use a hypothetical REST API (e.g., a "users" service) to keep it concrete.

---

### **Program.cs** — stdio transport with DI

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL for stdio: log to stderr only, stdout is the JSON-RPC channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient("UsersApi", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();   // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### **UserApiTools.cs** — tool class wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class UserApiTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<UserApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by their numeric ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The user's numeric ID (1-10)")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("UsersApi");
        return await client.GetStringAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search for users by name substring.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchUsers(
        [Description("Partial name to search for")] string query,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("UsersApi");
        var json = await client.GetStringAsync("/users", cancellationToken);
        var users = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<JsonElement>(json);

        var matches = users.EnumerateArray()
            .Where(u => u.GetProperty("name").GetString()!
                .Contains(query, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
            .Select(u => u.ToString());

        return $"[{string.Join(",", matches)}]";
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = false, Destructive = false),
     Description("Create a new user (POST to API).")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("User's full name")] string name,
        [Description("User's email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("UsersApi");
        var payload = new { name, email };
        var response = await client.PostAsJsonAsync("/users", payload, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK resolves dependencies **automatically** via two mechanisms:

| Style | How it works |
|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | Class receives services via primary constructor. Register the class's dependencies in `builder.Services`. The SDK instantiates the class per-request. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method params alongside tool params. The SDK distinguishes them: DI services are resolved from the container, tool params come from the LLM. |

**What's auto-injected (never appears in tool schema):**
- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IHttpClientFactory`, `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>` — any DI-registered service
- `IMcpServer` — server instance for notifications
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — progress reporting

**What appears in schema** (visible to the LLM):
- Parameters with `[Description("...")]` attributes — these are the tool's inputs

In the example above, `IHttpClientFactory` and `ILogger<UserApiTools>` are injected via the constructor. The LLM only sees `userId`, `query`, `name`, and `email` as callable parameters.

---

### Scaffold & verify

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiServer
# Replace the generated files with the code above, then:
cd MyApiServer && dotnet build
```

The server will start and wait for JSON-RPC messages on stdin — ready for VS Code, GitHub Copilot, or MCP Inspector to connect.
